english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Presented to Administrator Lee
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Administrator Lee of Suwon came to my humble dwelling and showed me his Record of the Eastern Campaign. I examined it with great care.

    In the fifth month of the year Eulhae, Lee was summoned from obscurity and appointed by court to serve as magistrate of Ulju. Upon taking office, he encouraged agriculture, trained troops, repaired fortifications and beacon towers, and prepared against unforeseen calamity. The following November, Japanese pirates reached his borders, yet dared not enter. Instead they ravaged Changi, advanced through Ninghai, and pressed toward Ulchin. The throne commanded Vice Premier Kim to assume supreme command, gathering forces from every province to strike both by water and land. Provincial Commander Choi and Governor Liu of Gyerim, commanding elite forces, marched forward and broke the pirate vanguard. The enemy retreated to Bamboo Mountain Island, feigning surrender. But no soldier trusted them.

    Governor Liu alone declared: "Victory through courage and good faith has been known since ancient times. How can we squander this moment through doubt?" He rode forth alone, bidding a messenger cry ahead: "The Governor of Gyerim approaches!" Five pirate chiefs then led hundreds of their men ashore, removing their armor to kneel and beg for mercy. Liu lectured them on righteousness: the fifth chief came to the capital to submit; the second left his son as hostage. Liu instructed them to proceed to Ulju Harbor for provisions. The chiefs obeyed, and Liu returned.

    In the twelfth month the pirates reached South Harbor, where Lee received them with courtesy. After five days, the fourth chief came with his men, urging Lee to board their vessel for wine. Lee went without hesitation. The pirate band surrounded him, armor gleaming, blades drawn, and challenged: "Why do you lure us to surrender, drawing us deep, only to encircle us by water and land?"

    Lee smiled and replied: "What strange words are these? Our sovereign bows to Heaven's mandate and answers to the people's will. His virtue reaches distant lands, and daily more come seeking refuge. All receive our true heart's welcome—have you not heard this already? For decades your people have bred chaos since the old dynasty's end. Our court deliberated sending great armies to sweep away your very nests. Yet now you come begging surrender! This is the hour when calamity transforms to fortune. To harbor doubt and betray faith, fleeing in the night—regret will chase you forever."

    The pirates moved toward violence but halted upon hearing his words. Yet they sailed on, forcing Lee to accompany them. He showed no trace of fear, telling his followers: "In life and death, in motion and stillness, all rests with Heaven. Harbor no doubt."

    When they reached Tsushima, a Buddhist monk came to greet him. The monk had some knowledge of poetry. Lee inscribed twenty characters and showed them:

    *The boundless sea seemed empty of all land,*
    *Yet sudden as dawn, a mountain rose before me.*
    *The monk who dwells here—pure and sublime—*
    *And facing him, I cannot help but smile.*

    The monk reported this to the island chief, who thereafter provided proper lodging and courtesy. Lee's followers, including Yi Cheong, repeatedly begged to steal a small boat and flee in secret. But Lee refused: "The ancients I admire would not take shortcuts through hidden paths. Our state will surely send an emissary. Speak no more of this."

    After a month, envoy Park Ingwi arrived and reproached the pirates for their treachery. Ashamed and repentant, they released Lee. The sovereign sent words of comfort and granted him his present rank, favoring service near the capital.

    I have long observed that a scholar's integrity cannot be judged in peaceful times—only when facing calamity and steadfastness is tested can we see what one truly holds. Lee, a single man caught among enemy hordes, with blades flashing before him and life hanging on each breath, remained composed and smiling. Through reasoned discourse he softened their savage hearts and awakened respect within them. Above, he kept faith with his sovereign; below, he preserved his own rectitude. Could any but one of true cultivation achieve this?

    I myself served three months as Governor of Gyerim, and Ulju falls under this jurisdiction. Thus I heard this tale from the elders. Now, reading his Record, I believe it all the more. The scholars of the province have memorized his twenty characters and requested that local literati compose poems in his honor. Therefore I set down here what I once heard.
  footnotes:
    - Eulhae year (을해년) refers to 1455, during the reign of King Sejong of Joseon
    - The Record of the Eastern Campaign (동행록) documents Lee's diplomatic mission and captivity among Japanese pirates
    - The poem's twenty characters (20자) reflect the poet's composure amid danger—a Buddhist teaching on perception transforming in crisis
